'''''Rosa'' 'Perle d'Or{{'}}''' is a [[garden rose|rose]] [[cultivar]] bred by Joseph Rambaux in 1875 and introduced by Francis Dubreuil in France in 1883.<ref name=hmfr>{{cite web |url=http://www.helpmefind.com/rose/l.php?l=2.4755 |title='Perle d'Or' |publisher=HelpMeFind |date= |accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref><ref name=classic>{{cite book |title=Klassische Rosen |publisher=DuMont |author=[[Peter Beales]] |page=360-361 |ISBN=3-8320-8736-2 |language= German |trans-title=Classic roses|date=2002}}</ref><ref name=meile>{{cite book |title=Alte Rosen - alte Zeiten |publisher= Wißner-Verlag |location=Augsburg |last1=Meile |first1=Christine |last2=Karl |first2=Udo |page=280 |ISBN= 978-3-89639-636-5 |language=de |trans-title=Old Roses - old times |date=2008}}</ref> 
Its parents were a double-flowered ''[[Rosa multiflora|R.&nbsp; multiflora]]'' seedling and the tea rose 'Madame Falcot' (Guillot, 1858).<ref name=P&R/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helpmefind.com/gardening/l.php?l=2.17084.1 |title='Madame Falcot' |publisher=HelpMeFindRoses |accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref> It is sometimes considered to be a [[Garden roses#China|china rose]] and sometimes considered a [[polyantha rose|polyantha]], and is also known as '''{{'}}Yellow Cécile Brünner{{'}}'''', as the pale apricot rose greatly resembles the related pale pink [[Rosa 'Cécile Brünner'|'Cécile Brünner']].<ref name=P&R/>

The small, full flowers have 26 to 40 [[petal]]s, forming small light rosettes with an average diameter of {{convert|4|cm|in}}.<ref name=RHSaz>{{cite book |title=Rosen – die große Enzyklopädie |publisher= Dorling Kindersley |author= Charles and Brigid Quest-Ritson |page=306 |ISBN=978-3-8310-1734-8 |language=de |trans-title=RHS Encyclopedia of Roses |date=2010}}</ref> Their colour is creamy amber with a hint of pink and ages to white, starting at the edges. Their fragrance is described as sweet and fruity, and varying in strength from light to strong.<ref name=hmfr /><ref name=classic /><ref name=RHSaz /> They develop from vermillion, long, ovoid buds and appear in large, long-stemmed clusters of 5 to 25 in flushes throughout the season.

'Perle d'Or' has well-branched shoots with glossy, medium to dark green foliage, and very few scattered, large [[prickle (botany)|prickles]]. The vigorous shrub grows densely, reaching {{convert|0.9|to|1.8|m|ft}} height at a width of {{convert|0.6|to|1|m|ft}},<ref name=classic /> and is winter hardy down to −20&nbsp;°C ([[USDA zone]] 6 to 7).<ref name=hmfr /><ref name=meile /> While the original form is a low shrub, a climbing [[sport (botany)|sport]] also exists (discovered before 1931).<ref name=P&R/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.helpmefind.com/rose/l.php?l=2.19368.1 |title='Perle d'Or, Cl.' |publisher=HelpMeFind |date= |accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref>

== Awards ==
''Rosa'' 'Perle d'Or' was granted several awards, including the Lyon Gold Medal in 1883,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.helpmefind.com/rose/l.php?l=2.4755&tab=18 |title='Perle d'Or' Rose Awards |publisher=HelpMeFind |date= |accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref> and the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/pdfs/agm-lists/agm_march2014-ornamentals |title=RHS AGM Listing March 2014 (Ornamentals) |publisher=[[Royal Horticultural Society|RHS]] |page=69 |accessdate=2014-09-04}}</ref>

